# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: etcd-store
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is essentially a service for distributed systems offering a hierarchical key-value store, which is used to provide a distributed configuration service, synchronization service, and naming registry for large distributed systems (see *Use cases*).
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper was a sub-project of Hadoop but is now a top-level Apache project in its own right.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper's architecture supports high availability through redundant services.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] Clients can ask another ZooKeeper leader if the first fails to answer.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper nodes store their data in a hierarchical name space, like a file system or a tree data structure.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] Clients can read from and write to the nodes and in this way have a shared configuration service.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper can be viewed as an atomic broadcast system, through which updates are totally ordered.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] The ZooKeeper Atomic Broadcast (ZAB) protocol is the core of the system.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is used by companies including Yelp, Rackspace, Yahoo, Odnoklassniki, Reddit, NetApp SolidFire, Meta, Twitter and eBay as well as open source enterprise search systems like Solr and distributed database systems like Apache Pinot.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is modeled after Google's Chubby lock service and was originally developed at Yahoo! for streamlining the processes running on big-data clusters by storing the status in local log files on the ZooKeeper servers.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] These servers communicate with client machines to deliver the required information.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper was developed to address issues that emerged during the deployment of distributed big-data applications.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] The services in the cluster are replicated and stored on a set of servers (called an "ensemble"), each of which maintains an in-memory database containing the entire data tree of state as well as a transaction log and snapshots stored persistently.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] Multiple client applications can connect to a server, and each client maintains a TCP connection through which it sends requests and heartbeats and receives responses and watch events for monitoring.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] In addition to the client libraries included with the ZooKeeper distribution, several third-party libraries, including Apache Curator and Kazoo, extend ZooKeeper's capabilities.
[src:etcd-store/apache-zookeeper] These libraries offer enhanced ease of use, additional features and support for a broader range of programming languages.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] etcd was originally developed as part of the CoreOS project, it was first announced in June of 2013.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] It was later donated to the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF).
[src:etcd-store/etcd] It became a CNCF incubating project in December 2018, and graduated in November of 2020.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] At the time, the maintainer team consisted of 10 members, including: Amazon, Google Cloud, IBM, Alibaba, and Red Hat.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] As of 2018, all 32 of the CFNFs Kubernetes compliant distributions and platforms used etcd as their datastore.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] According to a 2024 report by the CNCF, the project had over 3300 contributors and at least 450 contributing companies.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] The first stable version of etcd, v2.0.0, was released on January 28, 2015. v3.0.0 was released on June 30, 2016.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] The name "etcd" is derived from the Unix convention of storing system configuration files in the `/etc` directory, which applies to a single system, etcd stores configurations for a distributed system, hence the appended "d" standing for "distributed".
[src:etcd-store/etcd] On particular database entries, locks can be set to prevent writing by other entities while it is being used.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] Etcd was initially inspired by Chubby, a distributed lock manager developed Google in 2006, as well as Apache ZooKeeper.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] It supports TLS/SSL encryption, exposes a client-facing gRPC API, and supports multiversion concurrency control, and runtime cluster membership reconfiguration.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] The official IANA assigned ports for etcd are TCP 2379/2380.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] Etcd is used to store cluster data by default for most Kubernetes implementations, like AWS EKS.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] One notable exception being Google Kubernetes Engine, whose control-plane datastore was migrated from etcd to a Spanner-based store in 2024, while preserving etcd compatibility.
[src:etcd-store/etcd] Kubernetes also depends on the etcd API to communicate with its datastore, meaning that all storage backends used by it are required to support the etcd API.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:etcd-store/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] This document is meant to give an overview of the v3 etcd APIs central design.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] This should not be mistaken with etcd v2 API, deprecated in etcd v3.5.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] It is by no means all encompassing, but intended to focus on the basic ideas needed to understand etcd without the distraction of less common API calls.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] All etcd APIs are defined in gRPC services, which categorize remote procedure calls (RPCs) understood by the etcd server.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A full listing of all etcd RPCs are documented in markdown in the gRPC API listing.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Every API request sent to an etcd server is a gRPC remote procedure call.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] RPCs in etcd are categorized based on functionality into services.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] All RPCs in etcd follow the same format.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Each RPC has a function `Name` which takes `NameRequest` as an argument and returns `NameResponse` as a response.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] An application may read the `Cluster_ID` or `Member_ID` field to ensure it is communicating with the intended cluster (member).
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Applications can use the `Revision` field to know the latest revision of the key-value store.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] This is especially useful when applications specify a historical revision to make a `time travel query` and wish to know the latest revision at the time of the request.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Applications can use `Raft_Term` to detect when the cluster completes a new leader election.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The Key-Value API manipulates key-value pairs stored inside etcd.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The majority of requests made to etcd are usually key-value requests.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A key-value pair is the smallest unit that the key-value API can manipulate.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] In addition to just the key and value, etcd attaches additional revision metadata as part of the key message.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] This revision information orders keys by time of creation and modification, which is useful for managing concurrency for distributed synchronization.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The etcd client’s distributed shared locks use the creation revision to wait for lock ownership.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Similarly, the modification revision is used for detecting software transactional memory read set conflicts and waiting on leader election updates.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] etcd maintains a 64-bit cluster-wide counter, the store revision, that is incremented each time the key space is modified.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The revision serves as a global logical clock, sequentially ordering all updates to the store.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The change represented by a new revision is incremental; the data associated with a revision is the data that changed the store.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Internally, a new revision means writing the changes to the backend’s B+tree, keyed by the incremented revision.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Revisions become more valuable when considering etcd’s multi-version concurrency control backend.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The MVCC model means that the key-value store can be viewed from past revisions since historical key revisions are retained.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The retention policy for this history can be configured by cluster administrators for fine-grained storage management; usually etcd discards old revisions of keys on a timer.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A typical etcd cluster retains superseded key data for hours.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] This also provides reliable handling for long client disconnection, not just transient network disruptions: watchers simply resume from the last observed historical revision.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Similarly, to read from the store at a particular point-in-time, read requests can be tagged with a revision to return keys from a view of the key space at the point-in-time that revision was committed.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The etcd data model indexes all keys over a flat binary key space.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] This differs from other key-value store systems that use a hierarchical system of organizing keys into directories.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Instead of listing keys by directory, keys are listed by key intervals `[a, b)`.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] These intervals are often referred to as “ranges” in etcd.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Operations over ranges are more powerful than operations on directories.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Like a hierarchical store, intervals support single key lookups via `[a, a+1)` (e.g., [‘a’, ‘a\x00’) looks up ‘a’) and directory lookups by encoding keys by directory depth.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] In addition to those operations, intervals can also encode prefixes; for example the interval `['a', 'b')` looks up all keys prefixed by the string ‘a’.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] By convention, ranges for a request are denoted by the fields `key` and `range_end`.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The `key` field is the first key of the range and should be non-empty.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The `range_end` is the key following the last key of the range.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] If `range_end` is not given or empty, the range is defined to contain only the key argument.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] If `range_end` is `key` plus one (e.g., “aa”+1 == “ab”, “a\xff”+1 == “b”), then the range represents all keys prefixed with key.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] If both `key` and `range_end` are ‘\0’, then range represents all keys.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] If `range_end` is ‘\0’, the range is all keys greater than or equal to the key argument.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A transaction is an atomic If/Then/Else construct over the key-value store.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] It provides a primitive for grouping requests together in atomic blocks (i.e., then/else) whose execution is guarded (i.e., if) based on the contents of the key-value store.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Transactions can be used for protecting keys from unintended concurrent updates, building compare-and-swap operations, and developing higher-level concurrency control.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A transaction can atomically process multiple requests in a single request.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] For modifications to the key-value store, this means the store’s revision is incremented only once for the transaction and all events generated by the transaction will have the same revision.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] However, modifications to the same key multiple times within a single transaction are forbidden.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] All transactions are guarded by a conjunction of comparisons, similar to an `If` statement.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Each comparison checks a single key in the store.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] It may check for the absence or presence of a value, compare with a given value, or check a key’s revision or version.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Two different comparisons may apply to the same or different keys.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] All comparisons are applied atomically; if all comparisons are true, the transaction is said to succeed and etcd applies the transaction’s then / `success` request block, otherwise it is said to fail and applies the else / `failure` request block.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] After processing the comparison block, the transaction applies a block of requests.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The `ResponseHeader` included in each inner response shouldn’t be interpreted in any way.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] If clients need to get the latest revision, then they should always check the top level `ResponseHeader` in `TxnResponse`.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The `Watch` API provides an event-based interface for asynchronously monitoring changes to keys.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] An etcd watch waits for changes to keys by continuously watching from a given revision, either current or historical, and streams key updates back to the client.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Every change to every key is represented with `Event` messages.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Watches are long-running requests and use gRPC streams to stream event data.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A watch stream is bi-directional; the client writes to the stream to establish watches and reads to receive watch events.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A single watch stream can multiplex many distinct watches by tagging events with per-watch identifiers.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] This multiplexing helps reducing the memory footprint and connection overhead on the core etcd cluster.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] To read about guarantees made about watch events, please read etcd api guarantees.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Leases are a mechanism for detecting client liveness.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] The cluster grants leases with a time-to-live.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] A lease expires if the etcd cluster does not receive a keepAlive within a given TTL period.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] To tie leases into the key-value store, each key may be attached to at most one lease.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] When a lease expires or is revoked, all keys attached to that lease will be deleted.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Each expired key generates a delete event in the event history.
[src:etcd-store/learning-api] Leases are refreshed using a bi-directional stream created with the `LeaseKeepAlive` API call.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] etcd is designed to reliably store infrequently updated data and provide reliable watch queries. etcd exposes previous versions of key-value pairs to support inexpensive snapshots and watch history events (“time travel queries”).
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] A persistent, multi-version, concurrency-control data model is a good fit for these use cases.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] etcd stores data in a multiversion persistent key-value store.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The persistent key-value store preserves the previous version of a key-value pair when its value is superseded with new data.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The key-value store is effectively immutable; its operations do not update the structure in-place, but instead always generate a new updated structure.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] All past versions of keys are still accessible and watchable after modification.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] To prevent the data store from growing indefinitely over time and from maintaining old versions, the store may be compacted to shed the oldest versions of superseded data.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The store’s logical view is a flat binary key space.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The key space has a lexically sorted index on byte string keys so range queries are inexpensive.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The key space maintains multiple **revisions**.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] When the store is created, the initial revision is 1.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Each atomic mutative operation (e.g., a transaction operation may contain multiple operations) creates a new revision on the key space.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] All data held by previous revisions remains unchanged.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Old versions of keys can still be accessed through previous revisions.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Likewise, revisions are indexed as well; ranging over revisions with watchers is efficient.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] If the store is compacted to save space, revisions before the compact revision will be removed.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Revisions are monotonically increasing over the lifetime of a cluster.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] A key’s life spans a generation, from creation to deletion.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Each key may have one or multiple generations.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Creating a key increments the **version** of that key, starting at 1 if the key does not exist at the current revision.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Deleting a key generates a key tombstone, concluding the key’s current generation by resetting its version to 0.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Each modification of a key increments its version; so, versions are monotonically increasing within a key’s generation.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Once a compaction happens, any generation ended before the compaction revision will be removed, and values set before the compaction revision except the latest one will be removed.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] etcd stores the physical data as key-value pairs in a persistent b+tree.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Each revision of the store’s state only contains the delta from its previous revision to be efficient.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] A single revision may correspond to multiple keys in the tree.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The key of key-value pair is a 3-tuple (major, sub, type).
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Major is the store revision holding the key.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Sub differentiates among keys within the same revision.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Type is an optional suffix for special value (e.g., `t` if the value contains a tombstone).
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The value of the key-value pair contains the modification from previous revision, thus one delta from previous revision.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The b+tree is ordered by key in lexical byte-order.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Ranged lookups over revision deltas are fast; this enables quickly finding modifications from one specific revision to another.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Compaction removes out-of-date keys-value pairs.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] etcd also keeps a secondary in-memory btree index to speed up range queries over keys.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The keys in the btree index are the keys of the store exposed to user.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] The value is a pointer to the modification of the persistent b+tree.
[src:etcd-store/learning-data-model] Overall, etcd gets the revision information from btree and then uses the revision as key to fetch value from b+tree(As shown below).
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The name “etcd” originated from two ideas, the unix “/etc” folder and “d"istributed systems.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The “/etc” folder is a place to store configuration data for a single system whereas etcd stores configuration information for large scale distributed systems.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Hence, a “d"istributed “/etc” is “etcd”.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] etcd is designed as a general substrate for large scale distributed systems.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] These are systems that will never tolerate split-brain operation and are willing to sacrifice availability to achieve this end. etcd stores metadata in a consistent and fault-tolerant way.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] An etcd cluster is meant to provide key-value storage with best of class stability, reliability, scalability and performance.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Distributed systems use etcd as a consistent key-value store for configuration management, service discovery, and coordinating distributed work.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Many organizations use etcd to implement production systems such as container schedulers, service discovery services, and distributed data storage.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Common distributed patterns using etcd include leader election, distributed locks, and monitoring machine liveness.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Perhaps etcd already seems like a good fit, but as with all technological decisions, proceed with caution.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Please note this documentation is written by the etcd team.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Although the ideal is a disinterested comparison of technology and features, the authors’ expertise and biases obviously favor etcd.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The table below is a handy quick reference for spotting the differences among etcd and its most popular alternatives at a glance.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Further commentary and details for each column are in the sections following the table.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] ZooKeeper solves the same problem as etcd: distributed system coordination and metadata storage.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] However, etcd has the luxury of hindsight taken from engineering and operational experience with ZooKeeper’s design and implementation.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The lessons learned from Zookeeper certainly informed etcd’s design, helping it support large scale systems like Kubernetes.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Furthermore, etcd supports a wide range of languages and frameworks out of the box.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Whereas Zookeeper has its own custom Jute RPC protocol, which is totally unique to Zookeeper and limits its supported language bindings, etcd’s client protocol is built from gRPC, a popular RPC framework with language bindings for go, C++, Java, and more.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Likewise, gRPC can be serialized into JSON over HTTP, so even general command line utilities like `curl` can talk to it.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Since systems can select from a variety of choices, they are built on etcd with native tooling rather than around etcd with a single fixed set of technologies.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] When considering features, support, and stability, new applications planning to use Zookeeper for a consistent key value store would do well to choose etcd instead.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Consul is an end-to-end service discovery framework.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] It provides built-in health checking, failure detection, and DNS services.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] In addition, Consul exposes a key value store with RESTful HTTP APIs.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] As it stands in Consul 1.0, the storage system does not scale as well as other systems like etcd or Zookeeper in key-value operations; systems requiring millions of keys will suffer from high latencies and memory pressure.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The key value API is missing, most notably, multi-version keys, conditional transactions, and reliable streaming watches.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] etcd and Consul solve different problems.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] If looking for a distributed consistent key value store, etcd is a better choice over Consul.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] If looking for end-to-end cluster service discovery, etcd will not have enough features; choose Kubernetes, Consul, or SmartStack.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Both etcd and NewSQL databases (e.g., Cockroach, TiDB, Google Spanner) provide strong data consistency guarantees with high availability.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] However, the significantly different system design parameters lead to significantly different client APIs and performance characteristics.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] NewSQL databases are meant to horizontally scale across data centers.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] These systems typically partition data across multiple consistent replication groups (shards), potentially distant, storing data sets on the order of terabytes and above.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] This sort of scaling makes them poor candidates for distributed coordination as they have long latencies from waiting on clocks and expect updates with mostly localized dependency graphs.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The data is organized into tables, including SQL-style query facilities with richer semantics than etcd, but at the cost of additional complexity for processing, planning, and optimizing queries.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] In short, choose etcd for storing metadata or coordinating distributed applications.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] If storing more than a few GB of data or if full SQL queries are needed, choose a NewSQL database.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] etcd replicates all data within a single consistent replication group.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] For storing up to a few GB of data with consistent ordering, this is the most efficient approach.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Each modification of cluster state, which may change multiple keys, is assigned a global unique ID, called a revision in etcd, from a monotonically increasing counter for reasoning over ordering.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Since there’s only a single replication group, the modification request only needs to go through the raft protocol to commit.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] By limiting consensus to one replication group, etcd gets distributed consistency with a simple protocol while achieving low latency and high throughput.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The replication behind etcd cannot horizontally scale because it lacks data sharding.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] In contrast, NewSQL databases usually shard data across multiple consistent replication groups, storing data sets on the order of terabytes and above.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] However, to assign each modification a global unique and increasing ID, each request must go through an additional coordination protocol among replication groups.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] This extra coordination step may potentially conflict on the global ID, forcing ordered requests to retry.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The result is a more complicated approach with typically worse performance than etcd for strict ordering.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] If an application reasons primarily about metadata or metadata ordering, such as to coordinate processes, choose etcd.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] If the application needs a large data store spanning multiple data centers and does not heavily depend on strong global ordering properties, choose a NewSQL database.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] etcd has distributed coordination primitives such as event watches, leases, elections, and distributed shared locks out of the box (Note that in the case of the distributed shared lock, users need to be aware about its non obvious properties.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] These primitives are both maintained and supported by the etcd developers; leaving these primitives to external libraries shirks the responsibility of developing foundational distributed software, essentially leaving the system incomplete.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] NewSQL databases usually expect these distributed coordination primitives to be authored by third parties.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Likewise, ZooKeeper famously has a separate and independent library of coordination recipes.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Consul, which provides a native locking API, goes so far as to apologize that it’s “not a bulletproof method”.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] In theory, it’s possible to build these primitives atop any storage systems providing strong consistency.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] However, the algorithms tend to be subtle; it is easy to develop a locking algorithm that appears to work, only to suddenly break due to thundering herd and timing skew.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Furthermore, other primitives supported by etcd, such as transactional memory depend on etcd’s MVCC data model; simple strong consistency is not enough.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] For distributed coordination, choosing etcd can help prevent operational headaches and save engineering effort.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] etcd provides lock APIs which are based on the lease mechanism and its implementation in etcd.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The basic idea of the lease mechanism is: a server grants a token, which is called a lease, to a requesting client.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] When the server grants a lease, it associates a TTL with the lease.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] When the server detects the passage of time longer than the TTL, it revokes the lease.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] While the client holds a non revoked lease it can claim that it owns access to a resource associated with the lease.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] In the case of etcd, the resource is a key in the etcd keyspace. etcd provides lock APIs with this scheme.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] However, the lock APIs cannot be used as mutual exclusion mechanism by themselves.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The APIs are called lock because for historical reasons.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The lock APIs can, however, be used as an optimization mechanism of mutual exclusion as described below.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The most important aspect of the lease mechanism is that TTL is defined as a physical time interval.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Both of the server and client measures passing of time with their own clocks.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] It allows a situation that the server revokes the lease but the client still claims it owns the lease.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Then how does the lease mechanism guarantees mutual exclusion of the locking mechanism?
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Actually, the lease mechanism itself doesn’t guarantee mutual exclusion.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Owning a lease cannot guarantee the owner holds a lock of the resource.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] In the case of controlling mutual accesses to keys of etcd itself with etcd lock, mutual exclusion is implemented based on the mechanism of version number validation (it is sometimes called compare and swap in other systems like Consul).
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] In etcd’s RPCs like `Put` or `Txn`, we can specify required conditions about revision number and lease ID for the operations.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] If the conditions are not satisfied, the operation can fail.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] With this mechanism, etcd provides distributed locking for clients.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] It means that a client knows that it is acquiring a lock of a key when its requests are completed by etcd cluster successfully.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Why do etcd and other systems provide lease if they provide mutual exclusion based on version number validation?
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Well, leases provide an optimization mechanism for reducing a number of aborted requests.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] Note that in the case of etcd keys, it can be locked efficiently because of the mechanisms of lease and version number validation.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] If users need to protect resources which aren’t related to etcd, the resources must provide the version number validation mechanism and consistency of replicas like keys of etcd.
[src:etcd-store/learning-why] The lock feature of etcd itself cannot be used for protecting external resources.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft is not Byzantine fault tolerant; the nodes trust the elected leader, and the algorithm assumes all participants are trustworthy.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft achieves consensus via an elected leader.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] A server in a raft cluster is either a *leader* or a *follower*, and can be a *candidate* in the precise case of an election (leader unavailable).
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The leader is responsible for log replication to the followers.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] It regularly informs the followers of its existence by sending a heartbeat message.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Each follower has a timeout (typically between 150 and 300 ms) in which it expects the heartbeat from the leader.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The timeout is reset on receiving the heartbeat.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If no heartbeat is received the follower changes its status to candidate and starts a leader election.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft implements consensus by a leader approach.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The cluster has one and only one elected leader which is fully responsible for managing log replication on the other servers of the cluster.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] It means that the leader can decide on new entries' placement and establishment of data flow between it and the other servers without consulting other servers.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] A leader leads until it fails or disconnects, in which case surviving servers elect a new leader.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The consensus problem is decomposed in Raft into two relatively independent subproblems listed down below.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] When the existing leader fails or when the algorithm initializes, a new leader needs to be elected.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] In this case, a new *term* starts in the cluster.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] A term is an arbitrary period of time on the server for which a new leader needs to be elected.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Each term starts with a leader election.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If the election is completed successfully (i.e. a single leader is elected) the term keeps going with normal operations orchestrated by the new leader.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If the election is a failure, a new term starts, with a new election.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] A leader election is started by a *candidate* server.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] A server becomes a candidate if it receives no communication by the leader over a period called the *election timeout*, so it assumes there is no acting leader anymore.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] It starts the election by increasing the term counter, voting for itself as new leader, and sending a message to all other servers requesting their vote.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] A server will vote only once per term, on a first-come-first-served basis.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If a candidate receives a message from another server with a term number larger than the candidate's current term, then the candidate's election is defeated and the candidate changes into a follower and recognizes the leader as legitimate.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If a candidate receives a majority of votes, then it becomes the new leader.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If neither happens, e.g., because of a split vote, then a new term starts, and a new election begins.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft uses a randomized election timeout to ensure that split vote problems are resolved quickly.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This should reduce the chance of a split vote because servers won't become candidates at the same time: a single server will time out, win the election, then become leader and send heartbeat messages to other servers before any of the followers can become candidates.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The leader is responsible for the log replication.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Each client request consists of a command to be executed by the replicated state machines in the cluster.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] After being appended to the leader's log as a new entry, each of the requests is forwarded to the followers as AppendEntries messages.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] In case of unavailability of the followers, the leader retries AppendEntries messages indefinitely, until the log entry is eventually stored by all of the followers.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Once the leader receives confirmation from half or more of its followers that the entry has been replicated, the leader applies the entry to its local state machine, and the request is considered *committed*.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This event also commits all previous entries in the leader's log.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Once a follower learns that a log entry is committed, it applies the entry to its local state machine.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This ensures consistency of the logs between all the servers through the cluster, ensuring that the safety rule of Log Matching is respected.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] In the case of a leader crash, the logs can be left inconsistent, with some logs from the old leader not being fully replicated through the cluster.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The new leader will then handle inconsistency by forcing the followers to duplicate its own log.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] To do so, for each of its followers, the leader will compare its log with the log from the follower, find the last entry where they agree, then delete all the entries coming after this critical entry in the follower log and replace it with its own log entries.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This mechanism will restore log consistency in a cluster subject to failures.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The first four rules are guaranteed by the details of the algorithm described in the previous section.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The State Machine Safety is guaranteed by a restriction on the election process.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This rule is ensured by a simple restriction: a candidate can't win an election unless its log contains all committed entries.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] In order to be elected, a candidate has to contact a majority of the cluster, and given the rules for logs to be committed, it means that every committed entry is going to be present on at least one of the servers the candidates contact.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft determines which of two logs (carried by two distinct servers) is more up-to-date by comparing the index term of the last entries in the logs.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If the logs have a last entry with different terms, then the log with the later term is more up-to-date.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If the logs end with the same term, then whichever log is longer is more up-to-date.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] In Raft, the request from a candidate to a voter includes information about the candidate's log.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If its own log is more up-to-date than the candidate's log, the voter denies its vote to the candidate.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This implementation ensures the State Machine Safety rule.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If a follower crashes, *AppendEntries* and *vote* requests sent by other servers will fail.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Such failures are handled by the servers trying indefinitely to reach the downed follower.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If the follower restarts, the pending requests will complete.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If the request has already been taken into account before the failure, the restarted follower will just ignore it.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Timing is critical in Raft to elect and maintain a steady leader over time, in order to have a perfect availability of the cluster.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Typical numbers for these values can be 0.5 ms to 20 ms for *broadcastTime*, which implies that the programmer sets the *electionTimeout* somewhere between 10 ms and 500 ms.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] It can take several weeks or months between single server failures, which means the values are sufficient for a stable cluster.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] To address cluster membership change issues that can arise in Raft, the algorithm introduces joint consensus, a transitional configuration phase.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Once the joint consensus is done (that is, the special Cnew configuration entry is replicated to a majority of Cnew servers' logs), the system fully transitions to the new configuration.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The cluster leader will stop being leader and return to follower state.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Specifically, it will continue to replicate log entries, but will not count itself as majorities.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] If a server believes that a current leader exists, any RequestVote RPCs (RPCs to gather votes for a leader election) will be disregarded.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] An extension to Raft is log compaction, where each server takes snapshots of its committed entries and saves it to stable storage, along with the index of its last entry and the term in the snapshotted log.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] The leader occasionally sends its snapshots to servers that are lagging behind in its log.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] When the server receives this snapshot, it will either discard its entire log if it's superseded by the snapshot, or only the entries up to the latest one in the snapshot.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] While Raft aims to be an alternative of Paxos and more understandable than Paxos, several issues arise.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft uses a single leader model, where client requests, reads and writes, and log replications goes through a single leader.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This means that there is a single point of failure and a bottleneck in performance.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Furthermore, it does not scale with increasing server workload.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft's membership change system has not been formally verified to be correct.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This means that implementing it is very risky, as there can be many potential bugs and errors.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Diego Ongaro, one of the co-authors, has tried to create a formal safety proof, but there are no plans to continue developing it due to how complicated it is.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] In 2014, a safety bug was found relating to single server membership changes.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] Raft, like other consensus algorithms, ensures that there can never be an incorrect result under all non-Byzantine conditions.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] This means that Raft is not a Byzantine fault tolerant algorithm.
[src:etcd-store/raft-algorithm] A 2023 study found that blockchain systems based on Raft are vulnerable to Byzantine attacks because of the lack of authentication on the client side.
